<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="65" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,543,1325]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,615,640]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Head as 
<figureCitation box="[528,611,615,640]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–20" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1966]" captionTargetBox="[280,1304,210,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[244,1344,195,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 11–20. Megaselia balfourbrownei sp. n. male. 11. head. 12–15. hypopygium. 16. front tarsus. 17. hind femur. 18. hind tibia.19. wing. 20. base of wing of specimen with unforked vein 3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617697/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
. Cheek with 3 bristles and jowl with 2 that are longer and more robust. Postpedicels without SPS vesicles. Thorax brown. Two notopleural bristles and no cleft in front of these. Mesopleuron bare. Scutellum with an anterior pair of short hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown with numerous hairs that are longest at their rear margins, especially on T6. Venter gray and with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation box="[508,638,759,784]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–20" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1966]" captionTargetBox="[280,1304,210,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[244,1344,195,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 11–20. Megaselia balfourbrownei sp. n. male. 11. head. 12–15. hypopygium. 16. front tarsus. 17. hind femur. 18. hind tibia.19. wing. 20. base of wing of specimen with unforked vein 3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617697/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Figs 12–15</figureCitation>
. Legs yellow to a little dusky. Fore tarsus (
<figureCitation box="[1128,1211,759,784]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–20" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1966]" captionTargetBox="[280,1304,210,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[244,1344,195,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 11–20. Megaselia balfourbrownei sp. n. male. 11. head. 12–15. hypopygium. 16. front tarsus. 17. hind femur. 18. hind tibia.19. wing. 20. base of wing of specimen with unforked vein 3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617697/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4. Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.73 times its length. Hairs below basal half of hind femur longer than those of anteroventral row of outer half (
<figureCitation box="[1045,1131,831,856]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–20" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1966]" captionTargetBox="[280,1304,210,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[244,1344,195,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 11–20. Megaselia balfourbrownei sp. n. male. 11. head. 12–15. hypopygium. 16. front tarsus. 17. hind femur. 18. hind tibia.19. wing. 20. base of wing of specimen with unforked vein 3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617697/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). Hind tibia (
<figureCitation box="[1285,1368,831,856]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–20" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1966]" captionTargetBox="[280,1304,210,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[244,1344,195,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 11–20. Megaselia balfourbrownei sp. n. male. 11. head. 12–15. hypopygium. 16. front tarsus. 17. hind femur. 18. hind tibia.19. wing. 20. base of wing of specimen with unforked vein 3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617697/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) with about a dozen differentiated posterodorsal hairs before the deflection of the dorsal hair palisade onto the anterior face, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[969,1117,903,928]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–20" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1966]" captionTargetBox="[280,1304,210,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[244,1344,195,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 11–20. Megaselia balfourbrownei sp. n. male. 11. head. 12–15. hypopygium. 16. front tarsus. 17. hind femur. 18. hind tibia.19. wing. 20. base of wing of specimen with unforked vein 3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617697/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Figs 19 &amp; 20</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[1132,1295,903,928]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.725" metricValueMax="1.85" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" unit="mm" value="1.725" valueMax="1.85" valueMin="1.6">1.60–1.85 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.43–0.45. Costal ratios 3.5–3.7: 1.4–1.5: 1; or 1.7: 1, with vein 3 being unforked. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[151,342,975,1000]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.285" metricValueMax="1.45" metricValueMin="1.12" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" unit="mm" value="0.1285" valueMax="0.145" valueMin="0.112">0.112–0.145 mm</quantity>
long. Hair at base of vein 3 
<quantity box="[670,835,976,1000]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" unit="mm" value="0.025" valueMax="0.03" valueMin="0.02">0.02–0.03 mm</quantity>
long. With 3–4 axillary bristles, the outermost being 
<quantity box="[151,313,1012,1036]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" unit="mm" value="0.125" valueMax="0.14" valueMin="0.11">0.11–0.14 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere knob pale, almost white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,543,1325]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,346,1047,1072]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Recognition.</emphasis>
Of the available specimens all but one have a forked vein 3. In the keys of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundbeck, W." box="[1203,1395,1047,1072]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" refId="ref7421" refString="Lundbeck, W. (1922) Diptera Danica. Part UI. Pipunculidae, Phoridae. Wesley, London, 455 pp." type="book" year="1922">Lundbeck (1922)</bibRefCitation>
the latter runs to Group vii, couplet 34 lead 1 to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schmitz)" authorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[649,960,1084,1109]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscohalterata">
<emphasis box="[649,845,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">M. fuscohalterata</emphasis>
(Schmitz)
</taxonomicName>
[a synomym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Meigen)" authorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[1145,1425,1084,1109]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sulphuripes">
<emphasis box="[1145,1309,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">M. sulphuripes</emphasis>
(Meigen)
</taxonomicName>
], but it has a different hypopygium and dark halteres. The costal index ranges from 0.42 to 0.45. Those with the CI 0.44 or more run to Group VI couplet 37 lead 2 to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wood)" authorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[660,908,1156,1181]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subtumida">
<emphasis box="[660,812,1156,1181]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">M. subtumida</emphasis>
(Wood)
</taxonomicName>
, which has a different hypopygium and vein Sc running to vein 1. Specimens with the CI &lt;0.44 run to Group VII couplet lead 1 (see above). In the key to British species (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[244,391,1228,1253]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7235" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 20, but its hypopygium differs from the two species of this couplet and that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmitz" authorityName="Schmitz" authorityYear="1935" box="[151,376,1263,1288]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latericia">
<emphasis box="[151,280,1263,1288]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">M. latericia</emphasis>
Schmitz
</taxonomicName>
that runs to the same couplet. It has a different hypopygium (
<figureCitation box="[1049,1167,1263,1288]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[271,1255,201,1907]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[225,1277,186,1925]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Megaselia anniduedahlae sp. n. male (Figs 1-10). 1. Frons. 2. Postpedicels, palps and proboscis. 3, proboscis from below. 4, left face of hypopygium. 5. Right face of hypopygium. 6. Front leg. 7. segments 4 and 5 of front tarsus. 8. mid tibia. 9. Hind femur. 10. Wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617695/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
Figs 6 &amp; 
<quantity box="[1153,1167,1265,1288]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" unit="in" value="7.0">7</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[1201,1364,1263,1288]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" pagination="143 - 147" refId="ref7296" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (2011 a) Recognition of four poorly known European species of Megaselia Rondani (Dipt., Phoridae). Entomologist's Monthly Magazine, 146, 143 - 147. [2010]" type="journal article" year="2011">Disney, 2011a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
